First, Generate all rotations of the second word. Second, Check if any of these rotations is a substring of the first word.

Here's the implementation in Rust:

fn cycpattern_check(a: &str, b: &str) -> bool {
    let b_len = b.len();
    if b_len == 0 {
        return true; // An empty string is a substring of any string
    }

    let a_chars: Vec<char> = a.chars().collect();
    let b_chars: Vec<char> = b.chars().collect();

    for i in 0..b_len {
        let rotated: String = b_chars.iter().cycle().skip(i).take(b_len).collect();
        if a.contains(&rotated) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    false
}

fn main() {
    let result = cycpattern_check("hello", "ell");
    println!("{}", result); // Should print true

    let result = cycpattern_check("hello", "llohe");
    println!("{}", result); // Should print false
}

Explanation:

First, Check for Empty String: If the second word b is empty, it is considered a substring of any string, so we return true.
Second, Convert Strings to Vectors of Characters: This makes it easier to manipulate and generate rotations.
Third, Generate Rotations: For each position i in the second word b, generate a rotation by skipping the first i characters and taking the next b_len characters.
Fourth, Check for Substring: Use the contains method to check if the rotated string is a substring of the first word a.
Fifth, Return Result: If any rotation is found to be a substring, return true. If no rotations are substrings, return false.

This approach ensures that all possible rotations of the second word are checked against the first word efficiently.

